<subSubSection id="B48AB25A823024C540F9DA8AF40F5063" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" type="taxonomy">
<paragraph id="652CCABC30D81304A235A4DDBB71AEF3" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Taxonomy.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="371D318BD811A2DF07A95FE782A8244B" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
Described as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="BB661EC2C98654D89BFE3A230A18C5ED" baseAuthorityName="Staudinger" baseAuthorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lygephila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lygephila lubrosa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lubrosa">
<emphasis id="8DC9B031022CBC603BCF3861A20AFB1E" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Lygephila lubrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The original description does not contain any information about the genitalia structures. However, the male genitalia show some recognisable differences compared with those of the nominate subspecies.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D80D01095AC370E0AB2C6BEB1C8C64A1" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
There is no trustworthy information about the holotype and paratypes of this taxon. According to the information from the 
<taxonomicName id="CC3BAB665F186552A13BCE6FCA35DA2F" authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lygephila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
collection of IZIP, 
<normalizedToken id="AB2FE8DAAD6A684DAE5878E94EA2116F" originalValue="Stshetkins’s">Stshetkins's</normalizedToken>
collection was totally destroyed sometime after the end of the 1990's. Also, there are no corresponding type labels in 
<normalizedToken id="CCDA6BA47E7AE9841AE8C61E6DAAC13F" originalValue="institute’s">institute's</normalizedToken>
collection. To ensure the stability and identification of the taxon it is necessary to designate a neotype of 
<taxonomicName id="4BA81D2DD43C099DD283C95B0E41240B" authorityName="Stshetkin YuL &amp; Stshetkin YuYu, 1994" authorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lygephila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lygephila lubrosa subsp. orbonaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="lubrosa" subSpecies="orbonaria">
<emphasis id="567AFEC3101AB671E2CC972370DC2E2B" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Lygephila lubrosa orbonaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A28E766789F4D0A0DB486A07FFD5B81A" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="F4C9E0410D496A160DCF23CEB7E9C58B" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="785E1FDF556947AD8E759B83DA30503B" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
Differs from 
<taxonomicName id="D54F228EEA706535239B69C15C47DF45" authority="lubrosa" authorityName="lubrosa (Staudinger" authorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lygephila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lygephila lubrosa subsp. lubrosa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="lubrosa" subSpecies="lubrosa">
<emphasis id="5342CAF25093A1E98A90CB0176503903" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Lygephila lubrosa lubrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its smaller size and better marked reniform stigma. In the male genitalia, ssp. 
<taxonomicName id="E76A4DF37B4233F2DED7BA8886E92DFB" authorityName="Stshetkin YuL &amp; Stshetkin YuYu, 1994" authorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lygephila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="subsp. orbonaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="lubrosa" subSpecies="orbonaria">
<emphasis id="A709DD9191A1F601575DBF7C6D4B1980" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">orbonaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from ssp. 
<taxonomicName id="125DD8826C2390217A3DB2FA30AC8EEF" authorityName="lubrosa (Staudinger" authorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lygephila" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="subsp. lubrosa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="lubrosa" subSpecies="lubrosa">
<emphasis id="E5E642CB710129C136CE07FD64B3A324" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">lubrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its narrower uncus without a medial thickening, and the narrower upper part of valva with more expressed asymmetry.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3C025D5274183CA1ED6D0495B6D4A1C3" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" type="description">
<paragraph id="3585151B0ECFB127AF80DF0A5BB828A2" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1760D59EA384033F62D36F7286AEDBA2" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Wingspan 34-43 mm. The external features, with the exception of the smaller size and somewhat roundish forewing, match those of the nominate subspecies.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="209033A905B86E60BF3367D9744C61EF" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="16A7A4B699789A5484915873B07CA349" bold="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(Figs 
<figureCitation id="D1A12D77B13095DBA2B35D3C0C1D939D" captionStart="Figures 33–38" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 33 - 38. Clasping apparatus. 33, 34 Lygephila lubrosa lubrosa 33 neotype 35, 36 Lygephila lubrosa orbonaria 35 neotype 37, 38 Lygephila kazachkaratavika 37 neotype." pageId="7" pageNumber="114">35</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="6A8A1158D37FDAAD26A8333E39724052" captionStart="Figures 33–38" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 33 - 38. Clasping apparatus. 33, 34 Lygephila lubrosa lubrosa 33 neotype 35, 36 Lygephila lubrosa orbonaria 35 neotype 37, 38 Lygephila kazachkaratavika 37 neotype." pageId="7" pageNumber="114">36</figureCitation>
). Uncus long, stout, sabre-like, anal tube membranous with oval hardening of tissue - scaphial crown on scaphium and sclerotized fig on subscaphium; valva elongated, wide, with parallel margins in the middle, tapering to apex; clasper digitiform, strong, thickened with wide base, placed subapically, somewhat asymmetrical, left one short, right one longer, almost reaches costa. Aedeagus tubular with narrow, long, acute sclerotised lamina on ventral side of carina. Vesica globular, multidiverticulate, membranous; basal diverticulum small; medial diverticulum large with small lateral hemispherical bulging; 1st terminal diverticulum large, more or less wedge shaped, membranous with cauliflower-like part bearing numerous small pockets; 2nd terminal diverticulum large, cone shaped, scobinated on top; 3rd terminal diverticulum medial sized, bifurcated, Y-shaped; 4th terminal diverticulum large, bilobate, located opposite to 3rd medial diverticulum; terminal tube membranous, as long as aedeagus, opening point of terminal tube located near carina.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F0E5FD01DB3DCCEFDF0E8608A3C1591C" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="57069D272A3E9177F882F15180CD2B3D" bold="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Female genitalia.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
